x4freetext: -GAMMA EMISSION CROSS SECTIONS FOR 23 ELEMENTS USING
3.29 MEV NEUTRON INELASTIC SCATTERING-
STABILIZED 400 KV VAN DE GRAAFF ACCELERATOR,
OPERATED AT 300 KV AND 100 MICROAMP CURRENT.
THE NEUTRONS WERE PRODUCED BY THE D(D,N)3HE
REACTION.
.THE INCIDENT ENERGY OF 3.29 MEV WAS DETERMINED FROM
A VOLTAGE CALIBRATION AND A TABULATION OF NEUTRON
ENERGIES FROM CHARGED PARTICLE REACTIONS.FOR FURTHER
INFORMATION SEE A.H.JIGGINS AND J.S.BEVAN,J.SCI.
INSTR.,43(1966),478 AND J.B.MARION AND B.ALLEN,A
TABULATION OF NEUTRON ENERGIES FROM VARIOUS CHARGED
PARTICLE REACTIONS,U.S.ATOMIC ENERGY COMM.,REPORT
.THE SAMPLES OF THE NATURAL ELEMENTS WERE IN POWDER
FORM (PURITIES BETTER THAN 99PC) IN POLYTHENE
CONTAINERS (3.5CM HEIGHTX4CM DIAMETER), WHEIGHTING
BETWEEN 17.8 AND 132.6 G.
THE GAMMA RADIATION OF THE EXCITED TARGET
NUCLEI WAS DETECTED AND THE CORRESPONDING SIGNALS
FED TO A MULTI-CHANNEL ANALYZER.
A NAI CRYSTAL (7.6X7.6CM2), AT 90 DEG TO THE
NEUTRON BEAM SERVED AS THE GAMMA DETECTOR, COUPLED
TO A CANBERRA 1413 AMP AND A ND 2400 MULTICHANNEL
ANALYZER.
.THE PHOTOPEAK EFFICIENCY WAS DETERMINED BY USING
REFERENCE GAMMA SOURCES FROM AMERSHAM.
.THE FAST FLUX WAS MEASURED USING THE
REACTION 115IN(N,N ,GAMMA)115(M)IN WITH A METASTABLE
STATE AT 335 KEV.
.THE THERMAL COMPONENT (0.09PC OF THE FAST) WAS
DETERMINED BY THE REACTION 115IN(N,GAMMA)116(M)IN
WITH A METASTABLE STATE AT 417 KEV.
.THE BEAM STABILITY WAS MONITORED BY HARWELL 2000
SERIES BEAM MONITORING EQUIPMENT AND A LI-GLASS
DETECTOR.
.PHOTOPEAK AREA INTEGRATION BASED ON THE
CONVOLUTION TECHNIQUE BY A SAVITZKY AND M.J.E.GOLAY,
THE WELL-KNOWN 847 KEV LINE OF THE
REACTION FE(N,N ,GAMMA)FE(M) WITH A DIFFERENTIAL
CROSS SECTION BETWEEN 70.6 AND 68.0 MB/SR AT 90DEG
WAS  REFERENCE (MEAN OF FOUR DIFFERENT MEASUREMENTS
TAKEN,SEE J.LACHKAR ET AL.,NUCL.SCI.ENG.,55(1974),
168,R.B.DAY AND M.WALT,PHYS.REV.,117(1960),1330,K.
NISHIMURA,J.PHYS.SOC.JAPAN,16(1961),355,R.W.BENJAMIN
.THE HEADING ANG REFERS TO THE COMMON SCATTERING
ANGLE.
.DIFFERENTIAL CROSS SECTION DATA FOR GAMMA EMISSION
IN CONNECTION WITH INELASTIC NEUTRON SCATTERING
TAKEN FROM REFERENCE.
.CORRECTIONS WERE MADE FOR PROMPT RADIATION FROM THE
EXPERIMENTAL ENVIRONMENT DUE TO SCATTERED NEUTRONS
FROM TARGET AND SAMPLE,FOR DELAYED RADIATION DUE TO
ACTIVATION, FOR BREMSSTRAHLUNG BACKGROUND AND GAMMA
SELF-ABSORPTION IN THE SAMPLES.
.THE EXPERIMENTAL UNCERTAINTY WAS COMPOSED FROM THE
FOLLOWING CONTRIBUTIONS-
.8PC FOR THE FE-STANDARD.
.3.8 PC FOR EFFICIENCY CALIBRATION DUE TO THE SOURCE,
1.0 PC FOR GEOMETRICAL UNCERTAINTY DURING
CALIBRATION PLUS THE STATISTICAL ERRORS.
.1.0 PC FOR THE SELF-ABSORPTION CORRECTION.
.2.0 PC FOR NOT MAKING A CORRECTION FOR ATTENUATION
AND MULTIPLE SCATTERING.
.5.0 PC FOR THE INCIDENT FLUX MONITORING.
.1.0 PC FOR TIME-DEPENDENT BACKGROUND CORRECTION.
.0.5 PC DUE TO DEAD-TIME VARIATIONS IN THE ANALYZER.
.0.5 PC DUE TO POSSIBLE ERRORS IN WHEIGHTING AND
POSITIONING THE SAMPLES.
.STATISTICAL ERRORS.
.THE TOTAL ERRORS VARY BETWEEN 10.6 AND 14.6 PC.
.THE ENERGY-RESOLUTION OF THE DETECTION SYSTEM WAS
7.7 PC FOR THE 662 KEV LINE OF 137CS.
